<!DOCTYPE MAN SYSTEM "../../man.dtd">
<MAN>
  <LANGUAGE>eng</LANGUAGE>
  <TITLE>pinv  </TITLE>
  <TYPE>Scilab Function  </TYPE>
  <DATE>April 1993  </DATE>
  <SHORT_DESCRIPTION name="pinv"> pseudoinverse  </SHORT_DESCRIPTION>
  <CALLING_SEQUENCE>
  <CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>pinv(A,[tol])  </CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>
  </CALLING_SEQUENCE>
  <PARAM>
 <PARAM_INDENT>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>A  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
    : real or complex matrix
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>tol  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
    : real number
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
 </PARAM_INDENT>
  </PARAM>
  <DESCRIPTION>
  <P>
    produces a matrix <VERB>X</VERB> of the same  dimensions as <VERB>A&apos;</VERB> such that:
  </P>
  <P>
    <VERB>A*X*A = A, X*A*X = X</VERB>  and both
    <VERB>A*X</VERB> and <VERB>X*A</VERB> are Hermitian .
  </P>
  <P>
    The computation is  based  on SVD and  any  singular values 
    lower than a tolerance are treated   as zero: this  tolerance 
    is accessed by <VERB>X=pinv(A,tol)</VERB>.
  </P>
  </DESCRIPTION>
  <ITEMIZE label='REFERENCES'>
  <P>
 <VERB>pinv</VERB> function is  based on the singular value decomposition
 (Scilab function <VERB>svd</VERB>).
  </P>
  </ITEMIZE>
  <EXAMPLE><![CDATA[
A=rand(5,2)*rand(2,4);
norm(A*pinv(A)*A-A,1)
 ]]></EXAMPLE>
  <SEE_ALSO>
    <SEE_ALSO_ITEM> <LINK>rank</LINK> </SEE_ALSO_ITEM>     <SEE_ALSO_ITEM> <LINK>svd</LINK> </SEE_ALSO_ITEM>     <SEE_ALSO_ITEM> <LINK>qr</LINK> </SEE_ALSO_ITEM>
  </SEE_ALSO>
</MAN>
